our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development-professionals-network")) "Global development professionals network") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development-professionals-network")) "Transforming institutions hub") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development-professionals-network")) "Policy and advocacy") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development-professionals-network")) "Partnership") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development")) "Global development") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development")) "Private sector") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment")) "Global climate talks") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment")) "Climate change") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment")) "Green politics") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/science")) "Climate change") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "World news") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "Guardian Professional") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Editorial") (pubDate nil "Wed, 17 Apr 2013 16:17:00 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development-professionals-network/2013/apr/17/climate-change-collaboration-connect4climate") (dc:creator nil) (dc:subject nil "Global Development Professionals Network") (dc:date nil "2013-04-17T17:47:23Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407312510") (media:keywords nil "Global development professionals network, Transforming institutions hub, Policy and advocacy, Partnership, Global development, Private sector, Global climate talks, Climate change, Green politics, Climate change, World news") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/17/1366206825899/Alcantara-002.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Connect4Climate/Leigh Vogel/public domain") (media:description nil "The opening panel at the Alcantara dialogues with speakers from the worlds of fashion, architecture, production, government and international development. Photograph: Connect4Climate/Leigh Vogel")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/17/1366206833529/Alcantara-007.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Connect4Climate/Leigh Vogel/public domain") (media:description nil "The opening panel at the Alcantara dialogues with speakers from the worlds of fashion, architecture, production, government and international development. Photograph: Connect4Climate/Leigh Vogel")))) ("Letters: modern-day slavery – a worthy project" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/17624?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Amodern-day-slavery-letters%3A1895238&ch=Global+Development+Professionals+Network&c3=Guardian+Professional&c4=PRO%3A+Global+development+professionals+network%2CPRO%3A+Modern-day+slavery+%28GDPN%29%2CGlobal+development&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful&c6=Guardian+development+professionals+network&c7=2013%2F04%2F17+04%3A07&c8=1895238&c9=Article&c10=Letter&c13=PRO%3A+Views+and+reviews+%28GDPN%29%2CModern-day+slavery+in+focus&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Letters%3A+modern-day+slavery+%E2%80%93+a+worthy+project&c66=Guardian+Professional&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FGuardian+Professional%2FGlobal+Development+Professionals+Network%2FModern-day+slavery\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Focus on forced labour will lead to positive action and help campaigns globally</p><p>I am pleased to see that your focus is on all forms of labour. I have become quite critical of much anti-trafficking work. Too often organisations and media focus exclusively on the sex trade, which is horrific and inexcusable, yet only a part of the overall problem.</p><p></p><p>I work in Vietnam with Blue Dragon Children's Foundation. We have so far rescued 178 children and youth from garment factories, brothels, and forced marriage. We conduct these rescues ourselves, in conjunction with police where possible.</p><p></p><p><strong>Michael Brosowski</strong></p><p><em>Founder and CEO, Blue Dragon Children's Foundation and a 2011 'CNN Hero', Hanoi</em></p><p></p><h2>Forced labour and trafficking</h2><p></p><p>The International Organisation for Migration mission in Ukraine, highly appreciates your new series on modern-day slavery. Ukrainians are the biggest group among all victims of trafficking assisted by IOM, and estimates that since the year 2000 over 120,000 of Ukrainian women, men and children suffered from trafficking.</p><p></p><p>Currently we are dealing mainly with trafficking for labour exploitation and the majority of victims assisted by IOM Ukraine are men (56% in 2012 in comparison to 14% in 2004).</p><p></p><p><strong>Varvara Zhlukternko</strong></p><p><em>Communications and outreach officer, International Organisation for Migration</em></p><p></p><p><strong>Views and reviews is a weekly space to share the correspondence we get from our readers and also for our members to tell us what global development books you are reading. Sign up here to become a </strong><a href=\"https://register.guardian.co.uk/global-development/\" title=\"\"><strong>member</strong></a></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development-professionals-network/modern-day-slavery\">Modern-day slavery</a></li></ul></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development-professionals-network/2013/apr/17/modern-day-slavery-letters" (20846 47811) old 21 nil nil ((title nil "Letters: modern-day slavery – a worthy project") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development-professionals-network/2013/apr/17/modern-day-slavery-letters") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/17624?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Amodern-day-slavery-letters%3A1895238&ch=Global+Development+Professionals+Network&c3=Guardian+Professional&c4=PRO%3A+Global+development+professionals+network%2CPRO%3A+Modern-day+slavery+%28GDPN%29%2CGlobal+development&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful&c6=Guardian+development+professionals+network&c7=2013%2F04%2F17+04%3A07&c8=1895238&c9=Article&c10=Letter&c13=PRO%3A+Views+and+reviews+%28GDPN%29%2CModern-day+slavery+in+focus&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Letters%3A+modern-day+slavery+%E2%80%93+a+worthy+project&c66=Guardian+Professional&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FGuardian+Professional%2FGlobal+Development+Professionals+Network%2FModern-day+slavery\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Focus on forced labour will lead to positive action and help campaigns globally</p><p>I am pleased to see that your focus is on all forms of labour. I have become quite critical of much anti-trafficking work. Too often organisations and media focus exclusively on the sex trade, which is horrific and inexcusable, yet only a part of the overall problem.</p><p></p><p>I work in Vietnam with Blue Dragon Children's Foundation. We have so far rescued 178 children and youth from garment factories, brothels, and forced marriage. We conduct these rescues ourselves, in conjunction with police where possible.</p><p></p><p><strong>Michael Brosowski</strong></p><p><em>Founder and CEO, Blue Dragon Children's Foundation and a 2011 'CNN Hero', Hanoi</em></p><p></p><h2>Forced labour and trafficking</h2><p></p><p>The International Organisation for Migration mission in Ukraine, highly appreciates your new series on modern-day slavery. Ukrainians are the biggest group among all victims of trafficking assisted by IOM, and estimates that since the year 2000 over 120,000 of Ukrainian women, men and children suffered from trafficking.</p><p></p><p>Currently we are dealing mainly with trafficking for labour exploitation and the majority of victims assisted by IOM Ukraine are men (56% in 2012 in comparison to 14% in 2004).</p><p></p><p><strong>Varvara Zhlukternko</strong></p><p><em>Communications and outreach officer, International Organisation for Migration</em></p><p></p><p><strong>Views and reviews is a weekly space to share the correspondence we get from our readers and also for our members to tell us what global development books you are reading. Sign up here to become a </strong><a href=\"https://register.guardian.co.uk/global-development/\" title=\"\"><strong>member</strong></a></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development-professionals-network/modern-day-slavery\">Modern-day slavery</a></li></ul></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development-professionals-network")) "Global development professionals network") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development-professionals-network")) "Modern-day slavery") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development")) "Global development") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "Guardian Professional") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Letters") (pubDate nil "Wed, 17 Apr 2013 15:07:47 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development-professionals-network/2013/apr/17/modern-day-slavery-letters") (dc:creator nil) (dc:subject nil "Global Development Professionals Network") (dc:date nil "2013-04-17T15:07:47Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407368646") (media:keywords nil "Global development professionals network, Modern-day slavery, Global development") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/3/28/1332949320522/Royal-Mail-letter-box-stu-003.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Kevin Foy/Rex Features") (media:description nil "'We are carrying more mail, to more people, on larger rounds than ever. Our sacks are heavier. We work longer hours, and we've taken an effective pay cut.' Photograph: Kevin Foy/Rex Features")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/3/28/1332949326441/Royal-Mail-letter-box-stu-008.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Kevin Foy/Rex Features") (media:description nil "Correspondence after the launch of the Guardian series on modern-day slavery. Photograph: Kevin Foy/Rex Features")))) ("Redirect military expenditure to ensure a sustainable future" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/10965?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Aredirect-military-expenditure-sustainable-future%3A1894559&ch=Guardian+sustainable+business&c3=Guardian+Professional&c4=MIC%3A+Guardian+Sustainable+Business%2CFood+security&c5=Environment+Conservation%2CNot+commercially+useful&c6=Kumi+Naidoo&c7=2013%2F04%2F17+01%3A58&c8=1894559&c9=Blog&c10=Blogpost&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=MIC%3A+Sustainability+blog+%28GSB%29&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Redirect+military+expenditure+to+ensure+a+sustainable+future&c66=Guardian+Professional&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FGuardian+Professional%2FGuardian+sustainable+business%2FFood+security\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Global military spending was $1.75tn in 2012. With 19,000 children under five dying every day, <strong>Kumi Naidoo</strong> argues this money could be far better spent elsewhere</p><p>Last year $1.75tn was spent on the world's military, according to <a href=\"http://www.sipri.org/media/pressreleases/2013/milex_launch\" title=\"\">new estimates</a> released this Monday by the Stockholm International Peace Institute (SIPRI). Seems like a lot? Let me put this into perspective. This amount is the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_countries_by_GDP_%28nominal%29\" title=\"\">equivalent</a> of Canada's GDP or twice the GDP of the Netherlands.</p><p>Nato members together spent a trillion dollars on the military and despite a significant 6% decrease, the US remains firmly in the lead, accounting for about 40% of the global amount. With a considerable percentage of citizens' taxes both in America (where it's <a href=\"http://demilitarize.org/general/income-tax-money-federal-budget-2014-fiscal-year/\" title=\"\">up to 47%</a>) and across the globe going towards military expenses, surely people are entitled to question whether this is money well spent to ensure security. And how this spending is more justified than, say, investing in renewable energy, health care and education.</p><p>Consider this: every day <a href=\"http://www.unicef.org/mdg/index_childmortality.htm\" title=\"\">19,000 children</a> under the age of five die around the world, mainly from preventable causes. The costs of reducing mortality rates by two-thirds, improving maternal health as well as combating Aids, malaria and other major diseases, are estimated <a href=\"http://www.oecd.org/social/poverty/50463407.pdf\" title=\"\">to be $60bn</a>  (£39bn) a year. Meanwhile, $60bn is approximately the cost of buying and operating two nuclear ballistic missile submarines. The estimated total cost of achieving the six of the UN's <a href=\"http://www.un.org/millenniumgoals/\" title=\"\">millennium development goals</a> related to poverty, education and health – eradicating hunger, universal primary education, child mortality reduction, disease prevention– is $120bn annually in additional resources, a fraction of what is spent every year on militaries.</p><p>We at Greenpeace join the outcry against excessive military spending. Rather than spending money preparing for conflict, governments must focus their efforts on avoiding conflict and achieving sustainability and equity in their countries.</p><p>Climate change is a major driver of conflict and threat to international and national peace and security, putting billions of people's future in jeopardy. It is not often the case that we find ourselves in agreement with the military and intelligence communities, but when it comes  to the security implications of climate change, it seems we may have some similar concerns. In May 2012, <a href=\"http://www.defense.gov/news/newsarticle.aspx?id=116192\" title=\"\">US Secretary of Defence Leon Panetta said</a>: \"Climate change has a dramatic impact on national security: rising sea levels, to severe droughts, to the melting of the polar caps, to more frequent and devastating natural disasters all raise demand for humanitarian assistance and disaster relief.\"</p><p>These impacts of climate change are already being felt. Climate change and a carbon-intensive economy are already responsible for <a href=\"http://daraint.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/CVM_RELEASE_FINAL_ENGLISH.pdf\" title=\"\">5 million deaths</a> each year. By 2030, deaths could total 100 million. This is already costing <a href=\"http://daraint.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/CVM2ndEd-FrontMatter.pdf\" title=\"\">about $1.2tn</a> a year, which could double by 2030 if global temperatures are allowed to rise. So why is it that governments carry on spending $105bn a year on nuclear weapons, rather than diverting the amounts to mitigating the risks of the true WMD – \"weather of mass destruction\"?</p><p>Governments intent on spending taxpayers' money are fuelling the problem, rather than the solution. A <a href=\"http://www.imf.org/external/np/sec/pr/2013/pr1393.htm\" title=\"\">new report</a> by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) reveals that worldwide subsidies to fossil fuels total $1.9tn annually. Almost 9% of all annual country budgets are spent on supporting oil, natural gas and coal industries. Subsidies result in overconsumption of dirty energy, which fuels climate change. Eliminating subsidies would lead to a 13% decrease in global energy related CO2 emissions.</p><p>Moving <a href=\"http://www.greenpeace.org/international/en/publications/Campaign-reports/Climate-Reports/Point-of-No-Return/\" title=\"Greenpeace report\">away from fossil fuels</a> and investing in renewable energy is the world's best hope for avoiding the most serious impacts of climate change. In 2011, renewable energy provided more than 30% of new electricity production globally, up from less than 5% in 2005. In 2012, investments in renewable energy approximated $250bn – which employed 5 million people worldwide, a win-win situation. An <a href=\"http://www.greenpeace.org/international/en/campaigns/climate-change/energyrevolution/\" title=\"Greenpeace energy report\">energy revolution</a> in the power sector – moving away from climate-destroying fossil fuels and dangerous nuclear power – would require additional annual investments of $280bn – investments that would not only pay back financially but would significantly reduce the security threats resulting from climate change.</p><p>More than $3.5tn is spent annually on the world's military and on subsidising fossil fuels. We can no longer stand by and allow governments to spend recklessly on the wrong things, when so many right things remain neglected. Eradicating poverty and child mortality, and mitigating the destructive impacts of climate change could all be achieved if governments got their priorities right.</p><p><em>Kumi Naidoo is executive director of </em><a href=\"http://www.greenpeace.org/international/en/\" title=\"\"><em>Greenpeace</em></a><em>. He tweets </em><a href=\"https://twitter.com/kuminaidoo\" title=\"\"><em>@kuminaidoo</em></a></p><p><strong>This content is brought to you by </strong><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/guardian-professional\" title=\"Guardian Professional\"><strong>Guardian Professional</strong></a><strong>. Become </strong><a href=\"http://reg.guardian.managemyaccount.co.uk/sustainable-business/start.php\" title=\"a GSB member\"><strong>a GSB member</strong></a><strong> to get more stories like this direct to your inbox</strong></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development/food-security\">Food security</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/kumi-naidoo\">Kumi Naidoo</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/sustainable-business/blog/redirect-military-expenditure-sustainable-future" (20846 400