Return status: `exited abnormally with code 4
'
Command was `(wget -q -O - http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development/rss)'" "" (20849 20424 629421) obsolete 0 nil nil nil) ("Child slaves themselves will end slavery" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/12737?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Aresistance-child-slaves-end-slavery%3A1896421&ch=Global+development&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Universal+primary+education%2CGlobal+development%2CSociety%2CEducation%2CSlavery+%28News%29%2CWorld+news%2CHuman+trafficking%2CLaw&c5=Society+Weekly%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CEducation+Weekly+Education%2CSchools+Education&c6=Gordon+Brown+%28contributor%29&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+01%3A44&c8=1896421&c9=Blog&c10=Blogpost&c13=Modern-day+slavery+in+focus&c19=GUK&c25=Poverty+matters+blog&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=The+resistance+of+child+slaves+themselves+will+force+the+end+of+slavery&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FGlobal+development%2FUniversal+primary+education\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">A new anti-slavery coalition is campaigning for the right of every child to be free of exploitation and secured in education</p><p>Ratni was 14 years old when she was sold into slavery, handed over to a family friend who had promised her a better life. Forced into bonded labour as an unpaid domestic servant for one year in Delhi and then another in the Indian Punjab, Ratni has told of how she was raped by the man who was supposed to be her guardian.</p><p></p><p>She escaped only when, being trafficked through a rail station on her way to another year of bondage, she spotted a group of charity workers representing <a href=\"http://www.bba.org.in/\" title=\"\">Bachpan Bachao Andolan</a>, the Indian Save the Childhood Movement, and made her dash for freedom.</p><p></p><p>Only now that her sister has also been rescued from the same group can Ratni's story be told. Her ordeal – and that of many others – has stimulated 1m signatures in a petition to end child labour and child trafficking, and has helped persuade the Indian parliament to finally outlaw child trafficking.</p><p></p><p>Nanuska has not been so fortunate. She is a six-year-old Afghan girl. She was sold by her father to be married off at seven to a 17-year-old boy. The payment is to cover her mother's medical bills, but one condition of her sale is that her husband-to-be has banned her from going to school. I have written to President Hamid Karzai asking him to intervene to protect her.</p><p></p><p><a href=\"http://www.ei-ie.org/\" title=\"\">Education International</a>, the teachers organisation, has raised the case of a 12-year-old girl from Marrakesh, Raouia, told by the Moroccan education minister – whose duty it was to promote girls education – to leave school, go home and take up her \"proper\" role as a child bride.</p><p></p><p>It is because of situations like these – and the prevalence of child slavery and forced labour in Africa and Asia – that in Washington on Friday a new anti-slavery coalition on child labour, trafficking and marriage will assemble to campaign for the right of every child to be free of exploitation and secured in education. Focusing on global civil rights for children, international anti-slavery groups including the Global March Against Child Labour and <a href=\"http://www.walkfree.org/\" title=\"\">Walk Free</a> will join local and national groups, from the <a href=\"http://www.shaktisamuha.org.np/\" title=\"\">Shakti Samuha</a> in Nepal to the Cultura de Paz of San Salvador, to call for decisive action to ban child slavery by the end of 2015.</p><p></p><p>They will make the case that, with less than 1,000 days to go until the millennium development goals (MDGs) expire, the needs of the most marginalised children – the street child, bonded labourer, child bride, trafficked teenager – have been neglected. Without a plan to get their rights recognised now and in the <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development/interactive/2013/mar/26/future-of-development-timeline\" title=\"\">post-2015 framework</a>, these groups are in danger of being left further behind.</p><p></p><p>Ten million girls each year are forced into marriage, their lives put at risk by early pregnancy before they are mature enough to bear children. As many as 15 million children are denied even a single day of schooling because they have to go to work. This group represents one quarter of the world's 61 million children who are out of school – and the number of children working in Africa is rising.</p><p></p><p>The issue is receiving renewed attention, with a bill about to go before the Indian parliament to finally outlaw all forms of child labour. And, as will be discussed in Washington, there are direct and immediate actions that companies and individuals can take to end the practice. Georg Kell from <a href=\"http://www.unglobalcompact.org/\" title=\"\">Global Compact</a>, Guy Ryder from the <a href=\"http://www.ilo.org/global/lang--en/index.htm\" title=\"\">ILO</a> and I have written a <a href=\"http://www.unglobalcompact.org/docs/news_events/9.1_news_archives/2013_04_04/Final_Joint_Letter_Child_Labour.pdf\" title=\"\">letter</a> (pdf) to encourage all companies to remove all forms of child labour from every part of their supply chains. There are phone lines to raise the alert in some countries. This needs to be rolled out globally to ensure that a child who is trafficked from one country to another has access to support through a phone call or email. The <a href=\"http://www.polarisproject.org/\" title=\"\">Polaris Project</a>, based in Washington DC, is looking at developing such a programme.</p><p></p><p>But why does the problem of child slavery still exist when we made firm promises for progress on gender equality, child health and universal education through the MDGs? Because resources have not been sufficiently targeted at the most marginalised; those at the very bottom are making slower progress than those just above them. Yet while only education can break this cycle of structural disadvantage, basic education aid, currently just $3bn (£1.9bn), is being cut, and even at its peak averaged only $12 per child.</p><p></p><p>The most marginalised are now speaking out and will not wait for a slow-moving policy process. Look at the mushrooming of the groups of \"<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development/2012/oct/11/bangladeshi-girls-wedding-busters-child-marriage\" title=\"\">wedding busters</a>\" in Bangladesh – where girls are getting together to resist their parents' determination to marry them off and force them out of school. It is the energy, determination and impatience of these young freedom fighters that is forcing the pace of change. It is the resistance of child slaves themselves who will force the end of slavery – and we must be there to support them.</p><p></p><p><em>• Former UK prime minister Gordon Brown is the </em><a href=\"http://educationenvoy.org/\" title=\"\"><em>UN special envoy for global education</em></a></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development/universal-primary-education\">Universal primary education</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/slavery\">Slavery</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/law/human-trafficking\">Human trafficking</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/gordonbrown\">Gordon Brown</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development/poverty-matters/2013/apr/19/resistance-child-slaves-end-slavery" (20849 15377) old 5 nil nil ((title nil "Child slaves themselves will end slavery") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development/poverty-matters/2013/apr/19/resistance-child-slaves-end-slavery") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/12737?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Aresistance-child-slaves-end-slavery%3A1896421&ch=Global+development&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Universal+primary+education%2CGlobal+development%2CSociety%2CEducation%2CSlavery+%28News%29%2CWorld+news%2CHuman+trafficking%2CLaw&c5=Society+Weekly%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CEducation+Weekly+Education%2CSchools+Education&c6=Gordon+Brown+%28contributor%29&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+01%3A44&c8=1896421&c9=Blog&c10=Blogpost&c13=Modern-day+slavery+in+focus&c19=GUK&c25=Poverty+matters+blog&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=The+resistance+of+child+slaves+themselves+will+force+the+end+of+slavery&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FGlobal+development%2FUniversal+primary+education\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">A new anti-slavery coalition is campaigning for the right of every child to be free of exploitation and secured in education</p><p>Ratni was 14 years old when she was sold into slavery, handed over to a family friend who had promised her a better life. Forced into bonded labour as an unpaid domestic servant for one year in Delhi and then another in the Indian Punjab, Ratni has told of how she was raped by the man who was supposed to be her guardian.</p><p></p><p>She escaped only when, being trafficked through a rail station on her way to another year of bondage, she spotted a group of charity workers representing <a href=\"http://www.bba.org.in/\" title=\"\">Bachpan Bachao Andolan</a>, the Indian Save the Childhood Movement, and made her dash for freedom.</p><p></p><p>Only now that her sister has also been rescued from the same group can Ratni's story be told. Her ordeal – and that of many others – has stimulated 1m signatures in a petition to end child labour and child trafficking, and has helped persuade the Indian parliament to finally outlaw child trafficking.</p><p></p><p>Nanuska has not been so fortunate. She is a six-year-old Afghan girl. She was sold by her father to be married off at seven to a 17-year-old boy. The payment is to cover her mother's medical bills, but one condition of her sale is that her husband-to-be has banned her from going to school. I have written to President Hamid Karzai asking him to intervene to protect her.</p><p></p><p><a href=\"http://www.ei-ie.org/\" title=\"\">Education International</a>, the teachers organisation, has raised the case of a 12-year-old girl from Marrakesh, Raouia, told by the Moroccan education minister – whose duty it was to promote girls education – to leave school, go home and take up her \"proper\" role as a child bride.</p><p></p><p>It is because of situations like these – and the prevalence of child slavery and forced labour in Africa and Asia – that in Washington on Friday a new anti-slavery coalition on child labour, trafficking and marriage will assemble to campaign for the right of every child to be free of exploitation and secured in education. Focusing on global civil rights for children, international anti-slavery groups including the Global March Against Child Labour and <a href=\"http://www.walkfree.org/\" title=\"\">Walk Free</a> will join local and national groups, from the <a href=\"http://www.shaktisamuha.org.np/\" title=\"\">Shakti Samuha</a> in Nepal to the Cultura de Paz of San Salvador, to call for decisive action to ban child slavery by the end of 2015.</p><p></p><p>They will make the case that, with less than 1,000 days to go until the millennium development goals (MDGs) expire, the needs of the most marginalised children – the street child, bonded labourer, child bride, trafficked teenager – have been neglected. Without a plan to get their rights recognised now and in the <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development/interactive/2013/mar/26/future-of-development-timeline\" title=\"\">post-2015 framework</a>, these groups are in danger of being left further behind.</p><p></p><p>Ten million girls each year are forced into marriage, their lives put at risk by early pregnancy before they are mature enough to bear children. As many as 15 million children are denied even a single day of schooling because they have to go to work. This group represents one quarter of the world's 61 million children who are out of school – and the number of children working in Africa is rising.</p><p></p><p>The issue is receiving renewed attention, with a bill about to go before the Indian parliament to finally outlaw all forms of child labour. And, as will be discussed in Washington, there are direct and immediate actions that companies and individuals can take to end the practice. Georg Kell from <a href=\"http://www.unglobalcompact.org/\" title=\"\">Global Compact</a>, Guy Ryder from the <a href=\"http://www.ilo.org/global/lang--en/index.htm\" title=\"\">ILO</a> and I have written a <a href=\"http://www.unglobalcompact.org/docs/news_events/9.1_news_archives/2013_04_04/Final_Joint_Letter_Child_Labour.pdf\" title=\"\">letter</a> (pdf) to encourage all companies to remove all forms of child labour from every part of their supply chains. There are phone lines to raise the alert in some countries. This needs to be rolled out globally to ensure that a child who is trafficked from one country to another has access to support through a phone call or email. The <a href=\"http://www.polarisproject.org/\" title=\"\">Polaris Project</a>, based in Washington DC, is looking at developing such a programme.</p><p></p><p>But why does the problem of child slavery still exist when we made firm promises for progress on gender equality, child health and universal education through the MDGs? Because resources have not been sufficiently targeted at the most marginalised; those at the very bottom are making slower progress than those just above them. Yet while only education can break this cycle of structural disadvantage, basic education aid, currently just $3bn (£1.9bn), is being cut, and even at its peak averaged only $12 per child.</p><p></p><p>The most marginalised are now speaking out and will not wait for a slow-moving policy process. Look at the mushrooming of the groups of \"<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development/2012/oct/11/bangladeshi-girls-wedding-busters-child-marriage\" title=\"\">wedding busters</a>\" in Bangladesh – where girls are getting together to resist their parents' determination to marry them off and force them out of school. It is the energy, determination and impatience of these young freedom fighters that is forcing the pace of change. It is the resistance of child slaves themselves who will force the end of slavery – and we must be there to support them.</p><p></p><p><em>• Former UK prime minister Gordon Brown is the </em><a href=\"http://educationenvoy.org/\" title=\"\"><em>UN special envoy for global education</em></a></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development/universal-primary-education\">Universal primary education</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/slavery\">Slavery</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/law/human-trafficking\">Human trafficking</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/gordonbrown\">Gordon Brown</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development")) "Universal primary education") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development")) "Global development") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/society")) "Society") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/education")) "Education") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Slavery") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "World news") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/law")) "Human trafficking") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/law")) "Law") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Blogposts") (pubDate nil "Fri, 19 Apr 2013 12:44:01 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development/poverty-matters/2013/apr/19/resistance-child-slaves-end-slavery") (dc:creator nil "Gordon Brown") (dc:subject nil "Global development") (dc:date nil "2013-04-19T12:44:01Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407512978") (media:keywords nil "Universal primary education, Global development, Society, Education, Slavery, World news, Human trafficking, Law") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Environment/Pix/columnists/2013/4/19/1366374774351/MDG-children-play-footbal-003.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Vladimir Rys/Bongarts/Getty Images") (media:description nil "Children play football in South Africa, 2009. Only education can break the cycle of structural disadvantage. Photograph: Vladimir Rys/Bongarts/Getty Images")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Environment/Pix/columnists/2013/4/19/1366374780645/MDG-children-play-footbal-008.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Vladimir Rys/Bongarts/Getty Images") (media:description nil "Children play football in South Africa, 2009. Only education can break the cycle of structural disadvantage. Photograph: Vladimir Rys/Bongarts/Getty Images")))) ("Half of Syrian population 'will need aid by end of year'" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/94924?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Ahalf-syrian-population-aid-year%3A1896424&ch=World+news&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Syria+%28News%29%2CUnited+Nations+%28News%29%2CRefugees+%28News%29%2CArab+and+Middle+East+unrest+%28News%29%2CMiddle+East+and+North+Africa+%28News%29+MENA%2CWorld+news%2CAid%2CGlobal+development&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CCharities&c6=Martin+Chulov&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+01%3A43&c8=1896424&c9=Article&c10=News&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Half+of+Syrian+population+%27will+need+aid+by+end+of+year%27&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FWorld+news%2FSyria\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">UN high commissioner for refugees says crisis may be worst humanitarian disaster it has dealt with</p><p>More than half the population of Syria is likely to be in need of aid by the end of the year, the UN's high commissioner for refugees has warned, while labelling the ever-worsening crisis as the most serious the global body has ever dealt with.</p><p>António Guterres, who has led the UNHCR through the worst of the refugee crises in Afghanistan and Iraq, said the Syrian civil war was more brutal and destructive than both and was already the worst humanitarian disaster since the end of the cold war.</p><p>His assessment came as the UN released new data on the numbers of refugees, which revealed that 6.8 million Syrians are  in need of aid. That figure  is likely to reach at least 10 million, more than half the pre-war population of the country.</p><p>Another UN body, Unicef, says half of those currently in need are children.</p><p>\"I don't remember any other crisis where we are having 8,000 per day [fleeing across borders], every day since February,\" Guterres said in an interview with the Guardian. \"There will very likely be 3.5 million by the end of the year. We will have half the population of Syria in dire need of assistance and this is incomprehensible.</p><p>With the civil war now into its third year and increasingly taking the shape of a proxy regional war fought on a sectarian faultline, aid groups are making ever more strident predictions of a catastrophic funding shortfall.</p><p>Guterres goes further, warning that the modern boundaries of the Middle East and the post-Ottoman agreements that underpin them may unravel if the crisis is not brought to an end.</p><p>\"The political geography of the modern Middle East emerged from the Sykes Picot agreement with the exception of the never-resolved Israeli-Palestinian situation,\" he said of the Anglo-French deal at the end of the first world war that eventually formed the nation states of Syria and Lebanon. \"The conflict in Syria might for the first time put that political geography into question.\"</p><p>The US secretary of state, John Kerry, and Syrian leader, Bashar al-Assad, this week both warned of a partition of the country that would inevitably cause grave ramifications in neighbouring Lebanon, Iraq and Jordan and beyond.</p><p>Kerry appeared to advance the US position on Syria by suggesting an \"enclave break-up\" could only be prevented by getting \"everybody on the same page with respect to what post-Assad Syria will look like\".</p><p>Assad, meanwhile, reiterated his earlier warning that no country in the region would be safe if the Syrian war, in which a majority Sunni opposition is fighting a minority Alawite regime aligned to Shia Islam, led to the collapse of the embattled state's  borders.</p><p>UNHCR figures show that close to 1.3 million Syrians have fled the country in the past two years. The figure is markedly less than the numbers that left Iraq and Afghanistan over the past decade, but is increasing at a faster rate  than at any point in either country.</p><p>In addition, there are thought to be at least 3 million internally displaced Syrian refugees, many of whom have limited means to provide for themselves or their families. Communities in Syria's war-ravaged north, west and south are  largely without electricity and low on food and running water.</p><p>Refugee camps in northern Jordan, southern Turkey and Lebanon's Bekaa valley are overwhelmed with daily arrivals of refugees who have often made precarious journeys to escape nearby battlefields.</p><p>\"This is the most brutal [conflict], even with very brutal conflicts elsewhere,\" said Guterres. \"If one looks at the impact on the population, or the percentage of the total population in need, I have no doubt that since the end of the cold war it is the worst. And it will become even worse still if there is no solution.</p><p>\"My belief is that if we take all of these elements, then this is the most dramatic humanitarian crisis that we have ever faced. Then if we look at the geopolitical implications, I have no doubt that this is the most serious that we have ever dealt with.\"</p><p>Lebanon and Iraq are increasingly unable to deal with the Syrian spillover, which is disturbing already fraught sectarian power bases and straining meagre resources during an economic downturn brought on by the crisis.</p><p>\"There is a real threat to Lebanon and Iraq,\" said Guterres. \"Jordan is under serious economic stress. We have the Palestinian/Israeli question and the fact that the Syrian army has withdrawn from the Golan Heights. In the context of the Sunni-Shia divide, all the key actors are involved.</p><p>\"Even compared to Afghanistan, the geopolitical implications and the threat to global stability are profound. It's the most dangerous of all crises.\"</p><p>In an address to the United Nations security council on Thursday, Guterres said there had \"not been an inch of progress towards a political solution\".</p><p>Expanding on that to the Guardian, he said: \"It is of enormous frustration that we have come to such a situation in global governance that nobody can address it.\"</p><p>Diplomacy on Syria has failed to bridge a yawning divide in views on what has fuelled the crisis and how best to deal with it. Russia and China, two permanent members of the security council, have blocked moves towards more robust support of the opposition in Syria. The US and Europe have attempted to impose ever-tougher sanctions on the Assad regime, but have baulked at arming the opposition because of concerns about the influence of al-Qaida groups.</p><p>\"I lived in a bi-polar world,\" said Guterres. \"Until the war in Iraq, I witnessed a unipolar world with one single superpower. Now we are in a clearly established multi-polar world. New actors have emerged – the Brics: China, Russia, Brazil, India. There is no longer a clear set of power relations. There is no way to bring about consensus among global players, or to bring about  common action. There is no capacity to produce any solution.\"</p><p>UN appeals for aid to Syria remain desperately under-funded with some agencies, including Unicef, reporting a shortfall of more than 70%. The crisis was eased somewhat on Thursday when Kuwait transferred $300m to the UN for Syria relief. \"[It] will be distributed across all of our institutions,\" said Guterres. The Kuwaitis are the only country of the Gulf that has honoured its promise through the multilateral aid organisations.</p><p>\"We can now put some money up front in Syria, but we are all in big trouble. Most of the western countries have huge budget difficulties. Moving towards 3 million refugees, there is no way that this can be dealt with.</p><p>\"The system is at breaking point. There is limited capacity to take many more. Where are the people going to flee? Into the sea?\"</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/syria\">Syria</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/unitednations\">United Nations</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/refugees\">Refugees</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/arab-and-middle-east-protests\">Arab and Middle East unrest</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/middleeast\">Middle East and North Africa</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development/aid\">Aid</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/martin-chulov\">Martin Chulov</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/19/half-syrian-population-aid-year" (20849 15360) old 8 nil nil ((title nil "Half of Syrian population 'will need aid by end of year'") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/19/half-syrian-population-aid-year") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/94924?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Ahalf-syrian-population-aid-year%3A1896424&ch=World+news&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Syria+%28News%29%2CUnited+Nations+%28News%29%2CRefugees+%28News%29%2CArab+and+Middle+East+unrest+%28News%29%2CMiddle+East+and+North+Africa+%28News%29+MENA%2CWorld+news%2CAid%2CGlobal+development&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CCharities&c6=Martin+Chulov&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+01%3A43&c8=1896424&c9=Article&c10=News&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Half+of+Syrian+population+%27will+need+aid+by+end+of+year%27&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FWorld+news%2FSyria\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">UN high commissioner for refugees says crisis may be worst humanitarian disaster it has dealt with</p><p>More than half the population of Syria is likely to be in need of aid by the end of the year, the UN's high commissioner for refugees has warned, while labelling the ever-worsening crisis as the most serious the global body has ever dealt with.</p><p>António Guterres, who has led the UNHCR through the worst of the refugee crises in Afghanistan and Iraq, said the Syrian civil war was more brutal and destructive than both and was already the worst humanitarian disaster since the end of the cold war.</p><p>His assessment came as the UN released new data on the numbers of refugees, which revealed that 6.8 million Syrians are  in need of aid. That figure  is likely to reach at least 10 million, more than half the pre-war population of the country.</p><p>Another UN body, Unicef, says half of those currently in need are children.</p><p>\"I don't remember any other crisis where we are having 8,000 per day [fleeing across borders], every day since February,\" Guterres said in an interview with the Guardian. \"There will very likely be 3.5 million by the end of the year. We will have half the population of Syria in dire need of assistance and this is incomprehensible.</p><p>With the civil war now into its third year and increasingly taking the shape of a proxy regional war fought on a sectarian faultline, aid groups are making ever more strident predictions of a catastrophic funding shortfall.</p><p>Guterres goes further, warning that the modern boundaries of the Middle East and the post-Ottoman agreements that underpin them may unravel if the crisis is not brought to an end.</p><p>\"The political geography of the modern Middle East emerged from the Sykes Picot agreement with the exception of the never-resolved Israeli-Palestinian situation,\" he said of the Anglo-French deal at the end of the first world war that eventually formed the nation states of Syria and Lebanon. \"The conflict in Syria might for the first time put that political geography into question.\"</p><p>The US secretary of state, John Kerry, and Syrian leader, Bashar al-Assad, this week both warned of a partition of the country that would inevitably cause grave ramifications in neighbouring Lebanon, Iraq and Jordan and beyond.</p><p>Kerry appeared to advance the US position on Syria by suggesting an \"enclave break-up\" could only be prevented by getting \"everybody on the same page with respect to what post-Assad Syria will look like\".</p><p>Assad, meanwhile, reiterated his earlier warning that no country in the region would be safe if the Syrian war, in which a majority Sunni opposition is fighting a minority Alawite regime aligned to Shia Islam, led to the collapse of the embattled state's  borders.</p><p>UNHCR figures show that close to 1.3 million Syrians have fled the country in the past two years. The figure is markedly less than the numbers that left Iraq and Afghanistan over the past decade, but is increasing at a faster rate  than at any point in either country.</p><p>In addition, there are thought to be at least 3 million internally displaced Syrian refugees, many of whom have limited means to provide for themselves or their families. Communities in Syria's war-ravaged north, west and south are  largely without electricity and low on food and running water.</p><p>Refugee camps in northern Jordan, southern Turkey and Lebanon's Bekaa valley are overwhelmed with daily arrivals of refugees who have often made precarious journeys to escape nearby battlefields.</p><p>\"This is the most brutal [conflict], even with very brutal conflicts elsewhere,\" said Guterres. \"If one looks at the impact on the population, or the percentage of the total population in need, I have no doubt that since the end of the cold war it is the worst. And it will become even worse still if there is no solution.</p><p>\"My belief is that if we take all of these elements, then this is the most dramatic humanitarian crisis that we have ever faced. Then if we look at the geopolitical implications, I have no doubt that this is the most serious that we have ever dealt with.\"</p><p>Lebanon and Iraq are increasingly unable to deal with the Syrian spillover, which is disturbing already fraught sectarian power bases and straining meagre resources during an economic downturn brought on by the crisis.</p><p>\"There is a real threat to Lebanon and Iraq,\" said Guterres. \"Jordan is under serious economic stress. We have the Palestinian/Israeli question and the fact that the Syrian army has withdrawn from the Golan Heights. In the context of the Sunni-Shia divide, all the key actors are involved.</p><p>\"Even compared to Afghanistan, the geopolitical implications and the threat to global stability are profound. It's the most dangerous of all crises.\"</p><p>In an address to the United Nations security council on Thursday, Guterres said there had \"not been an inch of progress towards a political solution\".</p><p>Expanding on that to the Guardian, he said: \"It is of enormous frustration that we have come to such a situation in global governance that nobody can address it.\"</p><p>Diplomacy on Syria has failed to bridge a yawning divide in views on what has fuelled the crisis and how best to deal with it. Russia and China, two permanent members of the security council, have blocked moves towards more robust support of the opposition in Syria. The US and Europe have attempted to impose ever-tougher sanctions on the Assad regime, but have baulked at arming the opposition because of concerns about the influence of al-Qaida groups.</p><p>\"I lived in a bi-polar world,\" said Guterres. \"Until the war in Iraq, I witnessed a unipolar world with one single superpower. Now we are in a clearly established multi-polar world. New actors have emerged – the Brics: China, Russia, Brazil, India. There is no longer a clear set of power relations. There is no way to bring about consensus among global players, or to bring about  common action. There is no capacity to produce any solution.\"</p><p>UN appeals for aid to Syria remain desperately under-funded with some agencies, including Unicef, reporting a shortfall of more than 70%. The crisis was eased somewhat on Thursday when Kuwait transferred $300m to the UN for Syria relief. \"[It] will be distributed across all of our institutions,\" said Guterres. The Kuwaitis are the only country of the Gulf that has honoured its promise through the multilateral aid organisations.</p><p>\"We can now put some money up front in Syria, but we are all in big trouble. Most of the western countries have huge budget difficulties. Moving towards 3 million refugees, there is no way that this can be dealt with.</p><p>\"The system is at breaking point. There is limited capacity to take many more. Where are the people going to flee? Into the sea?\"</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/syria\">Syria</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/unitednations\">United Nations</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/refugees\">Refugees</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/arab-and-middle-east-protests\">Arab and Middle East unrest</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/middleeast\">Middle East and North Africa</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development/aid\">Aid</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/martin-chulov\">Martin Chulov</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Syria") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "United Nations") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Refugees") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Arab and Middle East unrest") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Middle East and North Africa") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "World news") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development")) "Aid") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development")) "Global development") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "News") (pubDate nil "Fri, 19 Apr 2013 12:43:44 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/19/half-syrian-population-aid-year") (dc:creator nil "Martin Chulov") (dc:subject nil "World news") (dc:date nil "2013-04-19T13:23:19Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407513208") (media:keywords nil "Syria, United Nations, Refugees, Arab and Middle East unrest, Middle East and North Africa, World news, Aid, Global development") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/19/1366375290493/Antonio-Guterres-005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Junior Kannah/AFP/Getty Images") (media:description nil "The UN high commissioner for refugees, António Guterres, said there had been 'not been an inch of progress towards a political solution' on Syria. Photograph: Junior Kannah/AFP/Getty Images")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/19/1366375297256/Antonio-Guterres-010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Junior Kannah/AFP/Getty Images") (media:description nil "UN high commissioner António Guterres, said there had 'not been an inch of progress towards a political solution' on Syria. Photograph: Junior Kannah/AFP/Getty Images")))) ("'The criticisms of the international response to Syria have been warranted'" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/55039?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Abritish-red-cross-sir-nick-young-syria%3A1896404&ch=Global+Development+Professionals+Network&c3=Guardian+Professional&c4=PRO%3A+Global+development+professionals+network%2CGlobal+development%2CUnited+Nations+%28News%29%2CWorld+news%2CICRC+-+International+Committee+of+the+Red+Cross%2CSyria+%28News%29&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CCharities&c6=Holly+Young&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+05%3A17&c8=1896404&c9=Article&c10=Interview&c13=PRO%3A+View+from+the+top+%28GDPN%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=%27The+criticisms+of+the+international+response+to+Syria+have+been+warranted%27&c66=Guardian+Professional&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FGuardian+Professional%2FGlobal+Development+Professionals+Network%2FUnited+Nations\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">British Red Cross chief executive Sir Nick Young talks about his vision for the organisation, the challenges of working in conflict zones and the importance of neutrality</p><p><strong>What is it like to be chief executive of the </strong><a href=\"http://www.redcross.org.uk/\" title=\"\"><strong>British Red Cross</strong></a><strong> (BRC)?</strong></p><p>I feel very fortunate to be working at an international aid agency because it really enables you to make a difference on a global scale, whether it is in emergency response, protecting those in conflict situations or preparing for disasters. It has, however, had its challenges. When I arrived in 2001, after being chief executive of Macmillan, there were financial problems, a failed restructuring and a crisis of confidence. We were spending more and earning less, and the organisation just didn't know where it was. I had to make a lot of redundancies so it was an extremely painful time. I have since had to work very hard to rebuild confidence within the organisation.</p><p>I think as a chief executive you need huge amounts of confidence and optimism. It is quite surprising how quickly organisations can turn in on themselves and be very self-critical, particularly in the voluntary sector. I see it as a key part of my role to keep people facing forwards and outwards. You have to stick to key priorities, know what you do well, and be prepared to say no – which is often very hard. While being chief executive at the BRC I have recognised that there are a million needs out there and we can't fulfil all of them.</p><p><strong>What is your vision for your organisation?</strong></p><p>We are in good shape now. We have a strong income and we are doing great work at home and overseas. My ambition for our work internationally is to put a lot more effort into building the capacity of Red Cross societies overseas to help them to respond to their own disasters and their own health care emergencies. There are now 186 national <a href=\"https://www.ifrc.org/en/what-we-do/disaster-management/responding/disaster-response-system/dr-tools-and-systems/red-cross-red-crescent-national-societies/\" title=\"\">Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies</a>, many of which are in Africa and south Asia where they don't necessarily have the financial resources to meet the needs they face in their country. It is incredibly important therefore to really develop the capacity of those societies to meet their own challenges.</p><p><strong>The BRC is currently running an appeal for Syria. What insights have emerged from your work there?</strong></p><p>The criticisms of the international response to Syria have been warranted: it has been belated and it has been too little. While we have launched an <a href=\"http://www.redcross.org.uk/syriacrisis\" title=\"\">appeal for Syria</a>, progress has been slow, and we undoubtedly need much more aid and support. Our experience there has confirmed that building capacity must begin before disaster or conflict strikes. It has also confirmed that the Red Cross needs to work much harder at getting our role – as a neutral and impartial actor – fully understood not only among governments and their armies, but among the opposition. This will enable us to have greater impact and reach those that need us. Working there has been extremely dangerous, and we need more support from governments and opinion formers around the world to help reduce the dangers for aid workers.</p><p><strong>How can we expect to see the BRC evolve over the next decade?</strong></p><p>You will become more aware of us because we are developing our advocacy work. We have always been an organisation that is strictly neutral and impartial, but we are not impartial in terms of meeting need. Neutrality and impartiality are key parts of our <a href=\"http://www.redcross.org.uk/About-us/Who-we-are/The-international-Movement/Fundamental-principles\" title=\"\">fundamental principles</a>, but I think that the organisation began to see these – in some situations – as a real gagging order on the way we operated. What we have recognised over the past few years is that in a conflict situation lives literally depend on us being impartial. But in other situations – if needs aren't being met – actually we should be anything but impartial.</p><p><strong>What is the future of development?</strong></p><p>Development and humanitarian assistance is at a crossroads. In terms of fundraising, people are increasingly questioning the impact organisations can actually have. Accountability and transparency are incredibly important for all of us and we need to get better at demonstrating the difference we can make with the help of people's support. We constantly need to justify our existence; we can never be complacent. The approach to emergency response is also evolving: the future is about disaster preparedness, resilience and local capacity building.</p><p><strong>Where did your interest in development come from and how has it led to where you are today?</strong></p><p>I started life as a commercial lawyer at one of the big city law firms. Although I enjoyed the excitement of the deals, I also became increasingly disillusioned with making big companies get bigger. I realised that the voluntary sector, in very general terms, was more likely to satisfy the urge I had to make a difference in the world. I initially worked at the BRC as director of UK operations before becoming chief executive of Macmillan. It was at Macmillan that I really learnt how to fundraise in a big organisation, which is a crucial for working in the voluntary sector, and something I took to my current role back at the BRC.</p><p><strong>Reflecting on your career, what would you say makes a good development leader?</strong></p><p>First, you have to be passionate: the day I stop being moved by what I see in the field, is the day I really need to get out. Second, it is important to maintain energy in the face of fearful odds. It is very easy to be demoralised by how much need there is out there, and sometimes what we can achieve feels like a drop in the ocean. Third, it is really important to believe in the people in your team and the local communities where you are working.</p><p><strong>Who is your development hero?</strong></p><p>First and foremost, I find heroes in the communities we see affected by disasters. It never ceases to amaze me how quickly people bounce back and begin to reestablish their lives. I have also been inspired by <a href=\"http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=109469979&privcapId=6659326&previousCapId=639004&previousTitle=SEAF\" title=\"\">Jan Egeland</a>, who was secretary general of the Norwegian Red Cross and then went on to become head of the <a href=\"http://www.unocha.org/\" title=\"\">United Nations Office for the Co-ordination of Humanitarian Affairs</a>. He was a fantastic example of someone who was never deterred by the scale of the challenge. He was able to shine a light on disaster situations and make sure that people listened.</p><p><strong>This content is brought to you by </strong><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/guardian-professional\" title=\"\"><strong>Guardian Professional</strong></a><strong>. To get more articles like this direct to your inbox, sign up free to become a member of the </strong><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development-professionals-network\" title=\"\"><strong>Global Development Professionals Network</strong></a></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/unitednations\">United Nations</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/international-committee-of-the-red-cross-icrc\">International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC)</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/syria\">Syria</a></li></ul></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development-professionals-network/2013/apr/19/british-red-cross-sir-nick-young-syria" (20849 28162) old 7 nil nil ((title nil "'The criticisms of the international response to Syria have been warranted'") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development-professionals-network/2013/apr/19/british-red-cross-sir-nick-young-syria") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.