quickly organisations can turn in on themselves and be very self-critical, particularly in the voluntary sector. I see it as a key part of my role to keep people facing forwards and outwards. You have to stick to key priorities, know what you do well, and be prepared to say no – which is often very hard. While being chief executive at the BRC I have recognised that there are a million needs out there and we can't fulfil all of them.</p><p><strong>What is your vision for your organisation?</strong></p><p>We are in good shape now. We have a strong income and we are doing great work at home and overseas. My ambition for our work internationally is to put a lot more effort into building the capacity of Red Cross societies overseas to help them to respond to their own disasters and their own health care emergencies. There are now 186 national <a href=\"https://www.ifrc.org/en/what-we-do/disaster-management/responding/disaster-response-system/dr-tools-and-systems/red-cross-red-crescent-national-societies/\" title=\"\">Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies</a>, many of which are in Africa and south Asia where they don't necessarily have the financial resources to meet the needs they face in their country. It is incredibly important therefore to really develop the capacity of those societies to meet their own challenges.</p><p><strong>The BRC is currently running an appeal for Syria. What insights have emerged from your work there?</strong></p><p>The criticisms of the international response to Syria have been warranted: it has been belated and it has been too little. While we have launched an <a href=\"http://www.redcross.org.uk/syriacrisis\" title=\"\">appeal for Syria</a>, progress has been slow, and we undoubtedly need much more aid and support. Our experience there has confirmed that building capacity must begin before disaster or conflict strikes. It has also confirmed that the Red Cross needs to work much harder at getting our role – as a neutral and impartial actor – 